{
  "title": "Designing a soft tech game",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "cb6de525e0b9c28b",
      "text": "Below is an overall description of the game design process we usually develop at les-ethers-fertiles.blog with Sophie Saradjian."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "97d88b72e1f9ade0",
      "text": "# Goal\n\nis not to gamify or make existing workflows fun without questioning them - so called gamification -, but rather to let people play with new distributed (I use \"distributed\" in the meaning of Paul Baran's centralized/decentralized/distributed network typology) workflows: including soft tech (communication, organization, governance, information aechitecture, ethics at work) and hard tech (opensource software, server space, evetually physical spaces etc)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9ab0cc88d1371f31",
      "text": "# Features of the games\n\n- **transnational, productive community oriented (coop enterprises, associations...)**: to be played by a group of 3-8 people that actually produce together towards the same goal, and use the same production infrastructure.\n- **productive**: when people play the games, they actually produce something for their current work\n- **hybrids**: there is a printed part (board, cards, pawns,dice) and a digital part (action cards are tiny tutorials of tasks to be completed on dedicated free/opensource software). One of the objective being to practice and experience as exhaustively a new workflow (communication-wise, information-wise, organization-wise,governance-wise,economically speaking).\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1840c2c2d8a71dc9",
      "text": "# Design process of a game\n\n1) I start with **a set of principles** (hacker ethics, free software, p2p economy, Nonaka & Takeushi knowledge model, documenting & publishing in public domain, [afterwards paycheck](https://lite.framacalc.org/darvoz) ...) I have read and actually experimented in existing organizations\n\n2) I define the **scope of the game** for it not to last more than 2-3 hours in average: its goal and what it will concretely produce for the team of players.\n\n3) I write down the **phases/big steps** of the games: they become the rounds of the game\n\n4) I define the **roles** for the players and the relationship between the roles: they become the role cards\n\n5) I define the **set of tools** (opensource apps) to be used by each role and the actions to be completed by each role: they become the action cards\n\n6) I go back and forth between steps 3),4) and 5) to make it consistent: I define an accurate **timing** for each action cards to be completed\n\n7) During step 6), generally I think of already existing games I played before and remix the game mecanics of 1 (or sometimes several of them). I pay a special attention to Roger Caillois 4 moods of the games: aleas, ilynx, mimicry and agon.\n\n8) I write down the **rules** of the game, with its specific **fiction**.\n\n9) I produce all the cards, the board with paper, pens, and basic collage\n\n10) I produce the designs of the collage for the cards and the board\n\n11) I test the timing of the game with players\n\n12) I go experiment and make some hard **designs with artists**: for example lasercutter of leather for the board, or serigraphic on textile, or simple on cardboard. (not completed yet)\n\n13) I **publish the game online**: text + svg and pdf files. Of 3d printing needed: stl files (didn't try 3d printed pawns yet)\n\n14) Small production and Animation process. **Iterations**."
    },
